00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:49.560
So could you tell us
more of that story?

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:51.720
MATT BEARD: Yeah, I'll
tell you about both prides.

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:54.930
Very, very different stories
in both those places.

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:57.780
I'm going to start
with Swaziland Pride.

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:02.730
I have the privilege to be there
myself for Swaziland Pride.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:06.230
This was also part of All Out's
global crowdfunding program.

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:11.380
So members from around 50
countries around the world,

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:14.220
including African
countries, all participate.

00:07:14.220 --> 00:07:17.610
An average gift of
just $19 came together

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:21.330
to enable all of the security,
the logistics, everything

00:07:21.330 --> 00:07:26.160
that was needed to run this
first ever pride in Swaziland.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.770
For those who don't know,
Swaziland is a tiny country.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:33.630
1.2 million people, just kind
of Northeast of South Africa.

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:38.130
It is the final absolute
monarchy in Africa

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:40.830
and it is illegal
to be gay there.

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:42.330
It is criminalized.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:44.460
And so when our
partners from Swaziland

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:48.120
came to us over a year ago
with the incredibly kind

00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:52.320
of audacious idea of
running pride in Swaziland,

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:54.150
we were super excited by it.

00:07:54.150 --> 00:07:59.760
Because it's rare to have
pride in Africa, anywhere.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:01.260
Uganda is one of
the few countries

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:05.610
that has managed, partially,
to pull off a pride event.

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:07.920
And that this tiny country
with an absolute monarchy,

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:10.050
with criminalized
homosexuality, that they

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:11.790
were going to take
this daring step,

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.180
we found incredibly exciting.

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:14.409
So we said, yes.

00:08:14.409 --> 00:08:16.200
We will go out and we
will raise the money.

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:21.220
And we reached the target
through this global support.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:23.190
It was a bumpy journey.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:26.190
We initially got all of the
police permissions in place.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:29.280
We had signed and
stamped documentation

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:33.960
that gave permission for this
public event to go ahead.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:36.840
But unfortunately, in the few
weeks leading up to the event,

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:39.780
as is often the case in
Africa, the Christian right

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:42.960
mobilized significantly.

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:45.450
They were placing editorials.

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:49.800
They started a digital
petition through a platform

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:55.290
called CitizenGO, which is kind
of the opposite alternative

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:56.320
of All Out, if you like.

00:08:56.320 --> 00:08:59.820
They use digital technology
and people power to campaign

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:03.990
against sexual and reproductive
rights and LGBTQ rights.

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:06.060
And they were able to
launch this petition, which

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:10.610
started to impact on the popular
discussion within Swaziland.

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:12.495
And that affected the police.

00:09:12.495 --> 00:09:15.570
So three days before the
event was due to start,

00:09:15.570 --> 00:09:18.301
the police just rescinded
all of the permissions

00:09:18.301 --> 00:09:19.800
that they'd given,
which they can do

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:22.480
because it's not a democracy.

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:26.550
And we had to work
really, really hard

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:30.000
with diplomatic
channels, et cetera,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.150
to bring that permission
back, which we did.

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.550
We did, with about
12 hours to spare.

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:37.500
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:40.209
MATT BEARD: And
during that time,

00:09:40.209 --> 00:09:42.000
there was a very, very
difficult discussion

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.110
about whether we would march
anyway, with all of the risks

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:47.070
that that entailed.

00:09:47.070 --> 00:09:49.020
We didn't come to
a final decision,

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:52.320
but the police permission
was put back in place.

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:56.510
Then we started to get
credible threats relayed

00:09:56.510 --> 00:09:59.490
through our private security
company of a firebombing that

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:01.800
would take place
during the march.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.860
And again a very, very difficult
decision, not made by All Out,

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:06.000
made by our partners.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.646
We always make sure that they
have agency in these things.

00:10:09.646 --> 00:10:12.020
But a very difficult decision
whether or not to go ahead,

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:15.360
but we decided we
would go ahead.

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:18.810
And so on a bright,
sunny Saturday morning--

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:19.780
it's winter there.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.350
It was warmish.

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:25.050
In this field that you can
see on the slides right now--

00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:27.090
it's a sports field--

00:10:27.090 --> 00:10:33.870
around 300 LGBT plus
people gathered.

00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:35.820
I need to really
emphasize with the guys

00:10:35.820 --> 00:10:38.290
that this was not only
the first ever pride,

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:40.110
but according to
our partners, this

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:43.440
was literally the first time
that more than about seven

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:47.280
or eight LGBT people had ever
come together in one place

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:49.460
at one time in this country.

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.770
And you can see the
joy on the faces.

00:10:51.770 --> 00:10:54.330
This is before we
even started marching.

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:58.350
It was incredibly moving,
even before we set off.

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:03.630
But once we set off to walk
probably 200 or 300 meters

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:07.710
through the city of Mbabane,
the capital of Swaziland,

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:10.050
I have to tell you that
I personally kind of lost

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:12.270
it and ended up in tears.

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.730
Because we didn't
have soundtracks.

00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:16.620
It's not London
or San Francisco,

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:23.340
but 300 people broke out in the
most beautiful African freedom

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:28.030
songs as we left this field
and marched onto the streets.

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:33.120
And it was truly a moment of
absolute personal liberation,

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:34.560
I think, for so many people.

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:38.280
You could see the people
were literally kind of dizzy

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:40.890
with excitement and joy.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:44.360
And so it was a really,
really special moment.

00:11:44.360 --> 00:11:46.695
It happened absolutely
without any incident.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:53.610
There was no violence, either
verbal or physical whatsoever.

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:57.440
We were able to come
back into the field.

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:00.840
There was then a
festival, and we

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:04.800
were even able to run a party
in a private venue that evening.

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:09.760
Again, some security
threats came through,

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:14.000
but it all went off
without a hitch.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.274
And going back to my
previous point, when

00:12:17.274 --> 00:12:18.690
we talked to our
partners and when

00:12:18.690 --> 00:12:21.720
we talked to some of the people
who were participating in this,

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:25.950
there was an enormous
sense of just being boosted

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:31.080
by a massive battery of
power, that people finally

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:32.220
felt powerful.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:35.160
They felt they had agency.

00:12:35.160 --> 00:12:38.700
And we believe that the
ramifications of this

00:12:38.700 --> 00:12:40.380
will go way beyond
Swaziland, that it

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:42.420
will go across the continent.

00:12:42.420 --> 00:12:47.970
Because it really was a
moment of significant success

00:12:47.970 --> 00:12:52.980
for an LGBT movement in
a hostile environment.

00:12:52.980 --> 00:12:57.930
So the same weekend, Istanbul
Pride was due to take place.

00:12:57.930 --> 00:13:05.460
And my colleague, Uri, was
there to stand shoulder

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:09.330
to shoulder with our
partners in Turkey.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.670
We've worked with them
for the last three years

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:14.560
around pride to
raise visibility.

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:15.990
We've run thunderclaps.

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:21.540
We've run petitions to ensure
that the world is watching.

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:24.360
Unfortunately, the same pattern
has happened for the last two

00:13:24.360 --> 00:13:25.185
or three years.

00:13:25.185 --> 00:13:27.030
It happened again.

00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:31.590
And I was telling Alex,
just as a side story--

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:36.680
because we're in a tech company,
I think this is interesting.

00:13:36.680 --> 00:13:38.680
I was in a hotel in Swaziland.

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:41.610
I happened to have a pretty
decent internet connection.

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:45.120
And there were lots of
Facebook Lives coming

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:49.020
from Pride in Istanbul as
things started to become

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:50.760
difficult and violent.

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:53.460
And I was actually able to
see my colleague on some

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:55.260
of those Facebook Lives.

00:13:55.260 --> 00:13:56.730
And was literally,
with WhatsApp,

00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:01.620
able to direct him out of
danger, as the police started

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:06.900
to engage, which I
found very, very surreal

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:12.520
and a real indicator, I guess,
of the power of technology.

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:16.380
But to continue with the
story of Istanbul Pride,

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:21.360
as I'm sure you all
know, Istanbul Pride

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:24.900
is an organization that applies
for permission every year

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:28.770
to run the pride
parade in Istanbul.

00:14:28.770 --> 00:14:32.640
They neither receive approval
nor denial each year,

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.470
so they go ahead
and do it anyway.

00:14:35.470 --> 00:14:38.640
And what usually happens is that
around 12 hours before they're

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.890
due to start,
there is a ban that

00:14:40.890 --> 00:14:43.380
is announced, which
is particularly cruel,

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:45.394
because it just doesn't
allow any planning,

00:14:45.394 --> 00:14:46.560
or any contingency planning.

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:52.310
In terms of negotiations
with the police,

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:54.470
it was agreed that
a statement could

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:58.290
be read out in four
places around the city

00:14:58.290 --> 00:15:00.890
by LGBT activists.

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:03.770
That happened, but
very, very soon after--

00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:08.540
literally minutes after--
the police, with dogs,

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:12.020
started to mobilize
around those four points

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:17.690
and gave people very, very
little time to disperse,

00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:19.460
and eventually engaged.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:22.970
And they used a lot of bullets.

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:24.620
They used tear gas.

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:29.150
They used dogs against
people who were completely

00:15:29.150 --> 00:15:35.570
peacefully claiming their
right to freedom of assembly.

00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:39.520
There was no registered
crime committed by anybody,

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:43.680
but people were viciously
attacked by the police

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:46.160
and by dogs.

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:48.500
We had a lawyer on
call, who's also

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:52.670
an activist, ready to help
out if my colleague, Uri, were

00:15:52.670 --> 00:15:55.990
arrested during that time.

00:15:55.990 --> 00:15:59.360
And he was simultaneously
beaten by 10 police officers

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:02.750
and attacked by a
dog, and had sustained

00:16:02.750 --> 00:16:08.000
very significant injuries to
his left leg during that attack.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:14.810
And so Istanbul is a
moment to pause for us,

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:18.780
a moment of reflection on
how far we still have to go.

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:23.480
It was a massive contrast to the
joy and liberation and agency

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:26.490
we saw in Swaziland.

00:16:26.490 --> 00:16:27.890
We're not giving up.

00:16:27.890 --> 00:16:31.162
We will continue to stand side
by side with Istanbul Pride.

00:16:31.162 --> 00:16:32.870
We're already talking
to them and working

00:16:32.870 --> 00:16:35.600
with them on, perhaps,
smarter strategies

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:39.814
next year to enable
this to happen

00:16:39.814 --> 00:16:41.480
in a way that won't
lead to people being

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:45.430
hurt in such brutal manner.

00:16:45.430 --> 00:16:46.370
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:48.380
Quite a contrast.

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:51.357
