00:20:57.810 --> 00:20:59.700
One of the things
I want to mention

00:20:59.700 --> 00:21:05.340
is we try and work on a
communications narrative

00:21:05.340 --> 00:21:08.460
that makes clear that,
particularly, in terms

00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:13.560
of British colonialism,
that it is actually

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:18.000
homophobia that is the
export, not homosexuality.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.030
So there are 52 commonwealth
countries in the world.

00:21:21.030 --> 00:21:24.210
37% of those,
shockingly, are still

00:21:24.210 --> 00:21:26.730
countries where it
is illegal to be gay.

00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:30.720
And most of those 37 countries,
even more shockingly,

00:21:30.720 --> 00:21:35.580
still have 19th century
British colonial legislation

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:37.290
that talks about
carnal knowledge

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:42.390
against the order of
nature, and criminalizes

00:21:42.390 --> 00:21:48.750
the act of, basically,
penetrative male gay sex.

00:21:48.750 --> 00:21:52.890
So we work on our
communications narrative

00:21:52.890 --> 00:21:55.270
that tries to flip that around.

00:21:55.270 --> 00:21:57.570
Because in many countries
around the world,

00:21:57.570 --> 00:21:59.910
there is an internal
homophobic narrative

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:03.950
that says homosexuality
has come from the West.

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:05.490
It's come from Europe.

00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:07.090
It's come from America.

00:22:07.090 --> 00:22:11.010
And we have to protect
"African" or "Caribbean"

00:22:11.010 --> 00:22:13.530
or "Latin American"
or "Asian" values

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:17.730
against this gay invasion.

00:22:17.730 --> 00:22:20.610
And what we've been
able to do, partially--

00:22:20.610 --> 00:22:23.820
it's a very big and long
job, it's a bumpy road--

00:22:23.820 --> 00:22:26.670
but is to kind of
invert that narrative.

00:22:26.670 --> 00:22:30.480
So for example, when the
Commonwealth heads of state

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:36.600
came to London for their summit
just a couple of months ago,

00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:41.670
we projected onto the
side of the UK parliament,

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:44.130
making clear that
in 37 countries

00:22:44.130 --> 00:22:47.360
of the 52 in the Commonwealth,
it is illegal to be gay.

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.290
and We were calling
on the UK government

00:22:49.290 --> 00:22:52.800
to apologize to the millions
of citizens of the Commonwealth

00:22:52.800 --> 00:22:56.280
for that legacy of
British colonial law.

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:01.560
But in terms of the second part
of your question of where that

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:06.190
comes from, where that
homophobia is rooted,

00:23:06.190 --> 00:23:08.864
and how we deal with
it politically--

00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:15.990
and I think it has to be
named, but it is often--

00:23:15.990 --> 00:23:18.330
religion is often
used or utilized

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:22.350
or exploited by
powerful elites in order

00:23:22.350 --> 00:23:26.680
to secure their positions.

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:29.760
So again, our
counter-strategy is really

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:31.950
to attempt to work
with progressive faith

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:33.690
as much as we can,
because we believe

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:38.920
it's one of the most important
ways to unlock that narrative.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:42.030
So just to give you another
example of a concrete campaign

00:23:42.030 --> 00:23:45.700
