00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:08.010
We bring together those
millions of ordinary voices.

00:28:08.010 --> 00:28:10.700
And together, those
voices raised the volume.

00:28:10.700 --> 00:28:12.110
They change hearts and minds.

00:28:12.110 --> 00:28:13.840
They change the conversation.

00:28:13.840 --> 00:28:16.805
And we believe passionately
in that theory of change.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.410
We call it new power.

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:24.830
Our founder, Jeremy Heimans,
has a book out right now called

00:28:24.830 --> 00:28:25.820
"New Power."

00:28:25.820 --> 00:28:29.030
And it's about
peer-driven, participatory,

00:28:29.030 --> 00:28:33.030
nonhierarchical change models.

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:37.390
But, or and, we also
believe that that is not

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:39.160
sufficient on its own.

00:28:39.160 --> 00:28:44.470
So our friends at HRC, who are
working on high-level advocacy

00:28:44.470 --> 00:28:46.760
in the corridors of power--

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:49.010
I mean, we have fewer friends
in the corridor of power

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:53.500
than we used to, but that is
also incredibly important work.

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:56.860
Our colleagues at Human Rights
Watch and Amnesty International

00:28:56.860 --> 00:29:00.340
who are documenting human
rights violations, that is also

00:29:00.340 --> 00:29:02.740
incredibly important work.

00:29:02.740 --> 00:29:04.570
Friends in the legal
profession, who

00:29:04.570 --> 00:29:08.620
are supporting strategic
litigation to challenge

00:29:08.620 --> 00:29:11.530
criminalisation of
homosexuality, that is also

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:13.400
incredibly important work.

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:15.610
So my personal
belief, really, is

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:18.980
that it is the combination
that is effective,

00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:21.270
that all of those different
theories of change

00:29:21.270 --> 00:29:24.070
are greater than the
sum of the parts.

00:29:24.070 --> 00:29:28.570
And when we can work effectively
together, it creates change.

00:29:28.570 --> 00:29:31.920
And I would actually take
that one step further--

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:35.080
and I know this is very kind of
vogue-ish to say in the United

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:38.170
States right now because of
the current environment that

00:29:38.170 --> 00:29:39.310
we're in--

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:42.790
but I think if you can make
it also intersectional,

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:44.990
then it's even stronger.

00:29:44.990 --> 00:29:47.590
So we've been really trying to
work with the gender justice

00:29:47.590 --> 00:29:50.140
movement, with the racial
justice movement here

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:53.320
and in the UK and in
the rest of Europe

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:55.240
to kind of form
intersectional alliances.

00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:59.620
Because so often, particularly
with gender justice,

00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:02.420
our enemies are actually
the same people.

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:05.884
And so I think its
really important

00:30:05.884 --> 00:30:06.800
that we work together.

00:30:10.265 --> 00:30:13.290
SPEAKER: Any more folks?

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:16.040
We can touch on a
couple of other things.

00:30:16.040 --> 00:30:19.850
I think we would be remiss
if we had you on Google

00:30:19.850 --> 00:30:22.362
and we didn't talk a little
bit about digital strategies.

00:30:22.362 --> 00:30:24.070
That is, really, the
core of what you do.

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:25.110
MATT BEARD: Absolutely.

00:30:25.110 --> 00:30:30.710
SPEAKER: And so we see a lot
of this, what is sometimes

00:30:30.710 --> 00:30:33.080
called, slacktivism,
right or I think

00:30:33.080 --> 00:30:35.660
you called it keyboard activism
one time in a conversation.

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:39.207
And there's this
questioning, does it actually

00:30:39.207 --> 00:30:40.040
accomplish anything?

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:43.040
Can I, sitting in my room
at home on the internet,

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:45.600
actually make an impact
elsewhere in the world?

00:30:45.600 --> 00:30:47.904
And obviously, All Out
believes that you can, right?

00:30:47.904 --> 00:30:49.820
So I'm curious about how
you think about that,

00:30:49.820 --> 00:30:52.590
and what kinds of things
people can do that are helpful,

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:55.581
what's less helpful, and how
we should think about that.

00:30:55.581 --> 00:30:57.080
MATT BEARD: Yeah,
so we passionately

00:30:57.080 --> 00:30:59.450
believe that you can.

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:02.390
We passionately
believe that you don't

00:31:02.390 --> 00:31:06.470
have to give blood, sweat,
and tears to be an activist.

00:31:06.470 --> 00:31:08.630
Obviously, if you
can, that's awesome,

00:31:08.630 --> 00:31:10.550
but not everybody
can or wants to.

00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:12.980
And there are ways
in which people

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:18.030
can use the power of virtual
activism, keyboard activism,

00:31:18.030 --> 00:31:20.420
slacktivism, whatever
you want to call it,

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:21.880
to make a difference.

00:31:21.880 --> 00:31:24.350
And the way that that
difference happens

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:26.450
is through a multiplier effect.

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:29.810
So me taking a digital
action on my own

00:31:29.810 --> 00:31:32.210
isn't really going
to change the world.

00:31:32.210 --> 00:31:37.020
But when I join my
voice with thousands,

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:40.190
hundreds of thousands, sometimes
millions of other people

00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:43.100
who are doing the same
thing at the same time

00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:47.030
and creating a moment
of energy, that does,

00:31:47.030 --> 00:31:49.460
actually, really create change.

00:31:49.460 --> 00:31:53.300
It creates change in
two ways, two main ways.

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:55.820
I think, firstly,
as I've mentioned

00:31:55.820 --> 00:31:58.050
before, it can kind of
change the conversation

00:31:58.050 --> 00:32:00.500
or change the narrative.

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:03.830
Sometimes we literally have
got hundreds of thousands

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:06.470
of people taking
action and talking

00:32:06.470 --> 00:32:10.040
about a particular campaign that
we're running at the same time.

00:32:10.040 --> 00:32:13.370
And whether we actually achieve
the final outcome or not,

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:16.430
that has actually moved
that conversation forward.

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:21.980
It has challenged the
counter-narrative, that

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:27.290
LGBT plus people off unable
to look after children,

00:32:27.290 --> 00:32:30.090
shouldn't be getting
married, spreading disease.

00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:31.630
Whatever that
counter-narrative is,

00:32:31.630 --> 00:32:34.070
it enables it to be challenged.

00:32:34.070 --> 00:32:36.410
And then on some
of our campaigns,

00:32:36.410 --> 00:32:41.500
we know that we have actually
achieved a concrete outcome.

00:32:41.500 --> 00:32:44.630
We try very hard
not to be greedy

00:32:44.630 --> 00:32:48.080
with attribution, because
of the cake metaphor

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:49.940
that I was talking
about earlier.

00:32:49.940 --> 00:32:51.481
Because sometimes
it's very difficult

00:32:51.481 --> 00:32:54.230
to know whether it
was the meeting HLC

00:32:54.230 --> 00:32:58.340
had with someone in government
or the public campaign

00:32:58.340 --> 00:32:59.870
that All Out did.

00:32:59.870 --> 00:33:04.040
But we know that we do
achieve concrete outcomes.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:05.870
I'll give you one
example where we

00:33:05.870 --> 00:33:09.290
know for sure because the
decision-makers told us.

00:33:09.290 --> 00:33:12.740
So there probably are
people in this audience

00:33:12.740 --> 00:33:15.560
for whom the name Steven
Anderson will ring a bell.

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:18.410
Steven Anderson is
the Arizona pastor

00:33:18.410 --> 00:33:23.410
who celebrated the deaths of
49 of our brothers and sisters

00:33:23.410 --> 00:33:27.650
at the Pulse nightclub
in Orlando in his church.

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:33.470
And pastor Anderson was planning
a speaking tour in South Africa

00:33:33.470 --> 00:33:36.170
to spread that
message of hatred,

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:39.470
so we ran a global petition.

00:33:39.470 --> 00:33:43.280
We collected a dossier
of evidence against him,

00:33:43.280 --> 00:33:45.380
and we presented that
to the interior ministry

00:33:45.380 --> 00:33:46.475
of South Africa.

00:33:46.475 --> 00:33:48.950
As some of you may know,
South Africa's constitution

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:52.535
is actually the most
pro-LGBT in the world.

00:33:52.535 --> 00:33:56.540
It has very significant
provisions around hate speech,

00:33:56.540 --> 00:34:02.120
and they responded positively
and denied him an entry visa.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:04.160
He got stuck at JFK.

00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:05.360
He couldn't travel.

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:08.210
He was not able to spread
that message of hatred.

00:34:08.210 --> 00:34:10.010
And they came back
to us directly

00:34:10.010 --> 00:34:13.580
to tell us that it was a
result of that people power,

00:34:13.580 --> 00:34:17.449
of that mass international
community coming together

00:34:17.449 --> 00:34:21.260
to draw attention to this
man's hate speech that

00:34:21.260 --> 00:34:25.520
led to the decision to deny
him that entry visa into South

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:26.960
Africa.

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:30.638
He then tried to change his
travel plans to go to Botswana.

00:34:30.638 --> 00:34:32.179
We didn't run a
campaign in Botswana,

00:34:32.179 --> 00:34:35.179
but the Botswana government just
followed the South African lead

00:34:35.179 --> 00:34:40.360
and then also denied him
an entry visa to travel.

00:34:40.360 --> 00:34:42.170
SPEAKER: That's a great example.

00:34:42.170 --> 00:34:44.980
And you also do I think a lot of
grassroots fundraising, right?

00:34:44.980 --> 00:34:45.290
MATT BEARD: Correct.

00:34:45.290 --> 00:34:46.790
SPEAKER: Can you
talk about how that

00:34:46.790 --> 00:34:48.100
works, sort of practically?

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:50.322
MATT BEARD: Yeah.

00:34:50.322 --> 00:34:51.830
When I came into
the organization

00:34:51.830 --> 00:34:55.639
2 and 1/2 years ago, it seemed
a bit counter-intuitive to me

00:34:55.639 --> 00:35:00.080
that we had a database
of hundreds and hundreds

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:03.800
of thousands of global citizens
who, by definition, wanted

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:06.540
to stand up for
LGBT plus people,

00:35:06.540 --> 00:35:08.960
but that we weren't
asking them for money

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:11.600
for our frontline partners,
like in Swaziland.

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:17.400
So in 2016, we tested a couple
of crowdfunding appeals,

00:35:17.400 --> 00:35:21.290
and they have the brand
name Grassroots Giving.

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:23.720
And it kind-- we were
kind of surprised at just

00:35:23.720 --> 00:35:25.670
how great the response was.

00:35:25.670 --> 00:35:28.400
People really wanted to feel
that they were contributing

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:32.660
directly to a tangible piece
of frontline service delivery,

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:33.770
or activism.

00:35:33.770 --> 00:35:37.580
So in 2016, we tested
this by running an appeal

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:41.512
to keep a shelter for homeless
LGBT youth open in Poland,

00:35:41.512 --> 00:35:43.970
and we were able to keep that
open right through the winter

00:35:43.970 --> 00:35:47.240
months so that the kids
who were in this place

00:35:47.240 --> 00:35:50.780
weren't thrown out into a very
cold climate, but also a very

00:35:50.780 --> 00:35:53.210
homophobic climate.

00:35:53.210 --> 00:35:57.170
And then we also ran a
crowdfunder for Uganda Pride

00:35:57.170 --> 00:35:59.720
in 2016.

00:35:59.720 --> 00:36:03.920
Both those reached the target,
so in 2017, we rolled this out.

00:36:03.920 --> 00:36:06.890
We now run one
every single month.

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:11.660
The defining moment, I
guess, for this program

00:36:11.660 --> 00:36:15.835
for us came in 2017 during
the Chechnya crisis.

00:36:15.835 --> 00:36:17.210
And for those who
are in the room

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:22.130
or on the call who don't
know what happened there,

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:26.930
in 2017 in Chechnya, the
state security forces

00:36:26.930 --> 00:36:30.860
started to illegally
kidnap and round up

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:33.140
men presumed to be gay or bi.

00:36:33.140 --> 00:36:36.680
They were taken to
illegal detention centers

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:39.650
outside the city of Grozny.

00:36:39.650 --> 00:36:45.010
They were tortured and, in
some cases, were murdered.

00:36:45.010 --> 00:36:47.960
It was the most
significant moment

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:51.290
of state-sponsored
persecution of LGBT

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:55.640
plus people since the Nazis.

00:36:55.640 --> 00:36:59.150
We had been a longtime partner
of the LGBT Russian LGBT

00:36:59.150 --> 00:37:03.470
network, which was
organizing evacuations

00:37:03.470 --> 00:37:06.230
of men who had either
survived the camps

00:37:06.230 --> 00:37:09.800
or who were at risk
of going into them.

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:13.010
And we said to them,
this is something

00:37:13.010 --> 00:37:16.250
we should run through our
Grassroots Giving program.

00:37:16.250 --> 00:37:21.609
And we thought we could raise--

00:37:21.609 --> 00:37:22.900
the sums we raised were modest.

00:37:22.900 --> 00:37:25.304
So we thought we
could raise $20,000.

00:37:25.304 --> 00:37:26.720
That would have
paid for, perhaps,

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:29.640
six or seven evacuations.

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:32.780
We hit Send on the email,
and within 23 minutes,

00:37:32.780 --> 00:37:34.400
we had reached that target.

00:37:34.400 --> 00:37:37.640
And we ended up
raising $250,000, which

00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:39.050
for an organization
like All Out,

00:37:39.050 --> 00:37:41.990
is a very large amount of money.

00:37:41.990 --> 00:37:46.130
And that came from over
120 different countries.

00:37:46.130 --> 00:37:51.050
It was a massive act
of global solidarity.

00:37:51.050 --> 00:37:54.440
And in those very,
very dark days,

00:37:54.440 --> 00:37:59.420
it was some form of
redemption, that there

00:37:59.420 --> 00:38:02.030
was this generosity around
the world and a willingness

00:38:02.030 --> 00:38:03.710
to stand up to that.

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:06.560
We also ran an absolutely
enormous petition,

00:38:06.560 --> 00:38:07.490
working with avowals.

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:11.450
1.2 million people
signed our petition.

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:13.970
Uri, my colleague, who I was
talking about earlier who

00:38:13.970 --> 00:38:17.900
went to Istanbul, went to
Moscow to deliver that petition.

00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:21.966
And he and our activist
partners were arrested in Moscow

00:38:21.966 --> 00:38:23.840
and were never able to
deliver that petition.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:26.300
We ended up having
to do it digitally,

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:29.940
and I'm sure it went
straight into the trash can.

00:38:29.940 --> 00:38:35.480
But that moment was very,
very special for us.

00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:37.490
So we continue to do
one of these appeals

00:38:37.490 --> 00:38:39.560
every single month.

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:43.760
Right now, we're raising
money for the mosque in Berlin

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:45.650
that I talked about earlier.

00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:51.140
But we've also ran appeals
for safe houses for people

00:38:51.140 --> 00:38:54.030
fleeing from ISIS.

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:58.880
We funded helplines for
survivors of anti-LGBT hate

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:01.760
crime community centers.

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:05.290
A beautiful project
in Kurdistan in Iraq

00:39:05.290 --> 00:39:09.540
to paint pro-LGBT murals
on public streets.

00:39:09.540 --> 00:39:14.000
So we continue to work with
our global network of partners

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:16.010
to see where there are
these projects that

00:39:16.010 --> 00:39:19.250
require these relatively
modest, but sometimes very

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:22.160
transformational,
injection of funds

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:23.450
in order to make a difference.

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:25.820
And we believe this is
another kind of form

00:39:25.820 --> 00:39:29.510
of catalyzing, catalyzing
movements, fueling

00:39:29.510 --> 00:39:32.015
movements around the world.

00:39:32.015 --> 00:39:32.640
SPEAKER: Great.

00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:35.098
Well, Matt, I want to thank
you so much for coming in today

00:39:35.098 --> 00:39:36.510
and chatting with us.

00:39:36.510 --> 00:39:38.540
And thanks for coming.

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:40.080
MATT BEARD: Thank you.

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:40.680
Thanks.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:43.430
